Scientists have found a way to detect stars that are related to each other
Astrophysicists at the University of California, Santa Cruz, have studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical uniformity in star clusters.
The discovery is expected to help researchers search for stars that are related to one another, that is, that originated in the same cluster.
The authors published their findings in the journal Nature, and a brief overview can be found on the university's website.
The reason for the similar chemical composition of the nearest stars is the turbulent mixing in the gas clouds that preceded the formation of the stars.
Even if a newborn star leaves the star cluster, its chemical composition can be used to determine its birthplace and the region of formation of its relatives.
Scientists had previously doubted that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to a difference in its chemical content from that of its relatives in the cluster.
The results of the simulations conducted by astrophysicists show that such differences should not occur.
In their study, the researchers used a supercomputer to simulate two streams of interstellar gas that together formed a cloud.
Over the course of millions of years, this object undergoes its own gravitational pull and transforms into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
Scientists added marker paints to the original gas flows and found that the rapid turbulent mixing in the clouds produced a high degree of chemical uniformity.
Astrophysicists believe that their study proves that it is possible to search for chemical relatives of stars and to determine the possible regions of formation of such objects.
