Recalling the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Allison and John Lewis have proposed a bill that would protect union organizing as a civil right.
"Where there are unions, there are middle-class jobs", says Allison, a Minnesota Democrat who is co-chair of the Congressional Progressive Caucus.
That's why I'm proud to present the Workers' Rights Amendment Act alongside the symbol of the civil rights movement, John Lewis.
This groundbreaking bill will give workers the same legal options for discrimination in union organizations as for other forms of discrimination, by stopping the forces of union opponents.
Amending the Labour Relations Act to allow workers who face discrimination for joining unions to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive compensation and fines - is a sensible and necessary initiative.
But this is certainly not a radical initiative - at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Allison, Lewis and the co-authors of the bill are proposing is to recall a very American thought.
Despite the attacks on unions in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country - Americans once supported countries around the world to adopt, expand and respect labor rights.
There was a time, as millions of Americans remember, when this country simultaneously defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution designed to ensure that the militarised autocracy of Hideki Tojo was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their unions played a role in shaping the new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that "the right of workers to organize, negotiate and collectively act is guaranteed".
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight D. Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that guaranteed that Adolf Hitler's fascism would be replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to organize and be heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that stated explicitly: "The right to form associations for the purpose of protecting and improving labor and economic conditions shall be guaranteed to every person and to every profession or field of activity.
Agreements which restrict or seek to impair this right shall have no legal force; measures directed at these ends shall be declared unlawful.
When former first lady Eleanor Roosevelt was chair of the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which would be adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a world treaty, Roosevelt and the framers included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions for the protection of his interests".
For generations, Americans have taken for granted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to build civil and democratic societies, the Americans explained that the right to organize unions - and for these unions to participate as equal partners in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies - must be protected.
Now that these rights are under attack in America, it is wise, indeed, to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement did not undermine the strength of the nation, but increased it.
By raising the living standards of millions, the unions miraculously created a market for industry and raised the nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers, and so should we.
Official recognition of labor rights as human rights - and expanded protection of civil rights to prevent discrimination against trade union organizations - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis revive the ideals that historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
A judge is temporarily blocking a law that could shut down all abortion clinics in Louisiana.
In the United States, a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the passage of a Louisiana law that supporters say will likely shut down all five abortion clinics in the state.
Under the measure, which was signed into law by Louisiana Governor Bobby Jinald in June and was set to take effect on September 1, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have authority to admit patients to a hospital within 30 miles of their practice.
However, the judge's decision means that for now, doctors can continue to perform legal abortions while continuing to seek such authorization.
"The plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally while pursuing their claims", Judge John deGravells wrote in his decision.
The hearing will be scheduled within a month, at which time the judge will issue a more permanent ruling on this law.
Abortion advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a series of decisions against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to obtain hospital authorization.
"Today's decision ensures that Louisiana women are protected from a insidious law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights", said Nancy Northup, president and CEO of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which filed a lawsuit to stop the law on behalf of three of the state's five clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision applied to doctors from two clinics who were not plaintiffs in the case and also applied for admission authority.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have passed similar laws, and courts recently ruled such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of a Texas law that would have shut down most of the remaining clinics in the state were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion advocates, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say that the laws on abortion authority place restrictions on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion argue that such measures are aimed at protecting women's health, although some have also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has hospital admission authority, the Center for Reproductive Rights reports.
If all other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing the procedure, this doctor would, for fear of his safety, stop performing the procedure, the group said.
In criticism of the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish doctors who perform abortions while their applications for admission are pending.
What will the introduction of quotas for domestic products lead to ?
At least half of the products in the range of trade networks should be Russian, says Oleg Nilov, a state Duma deputy from the Fair Russia faction.
The parliamentarian has prepared a bill aimed at introducing protective measures against domestic producers, the newspaper "Izvestia" writes.
The document will be further detailed to avoid any possible discomfort for buyers.
This applies to products that are not produced in Russia, and for the rest of the product groups that are produced in Russia, the retailer will have to provide at least half of its shelves to domestic producers", - said N. Nilov.
Along with amendments to the article "On the Basics of State Regulation of Trade Activity in the Russian Federation", the bill provides for amendments to the Tax Code, setting a reduced rate of VAT of 10% when selling products produced in Russia.
The idea of introducing a 50% quota in the retail chains is part of a package of incentives for Russian producers.
There will be several times more domestic goods on the shelves.
However, the initiative can have both positive and negative effects, experts say.
According to the lawyer of the company "Taxman", member of the independent expert center "Public Duma" Sergei Litvinenko, for the Russian economy, as well as for the domestic agricultural and food industries, the effect will be positive, and will lead to growth.
It's a plus for farmers, small shops.
They'll be able to sell more, which means that profits will increase.
They will also have the right to dictate their terms and prices to retailers, who will be forced to buy their products.
Russian producers will be able to increase their activities and sales, which will lead to higher taxes than before.
It will increase budget revenues, create new jobs, some industries will expand, some will develop faster, contribute to GDP growth.
Russia's dependence on foreign food will decrease several times, but not immediately", the expert notes.
Previously, Russian enterprises often could not get into the local stores due to the high competition from foreign counterparts.
Now that the embargo is in place, that niche is free and you can breathe a sigh of relief.
But we should not forget that after all the necessary approvals and sanitary inspections, food products from Latin America, Turkey and Serbia will enter the Russian market.
In other words, it's a moment of silence, when the old players have left and the new ones have not yet arrived.
Almost a month later, we can talk about increased demand for domestic raw materials, as well as the increase in prices for finished products", - told AiF.ru the first Vice-President of the all-Russian public organization "Russian club of financial directors", Tamara Kasyanova.
Clearly, the idea of selling at least 50% of Russian food products in each category will allow the sector to be consolidated with local producers.
In this case, they will compete with each other, not with goods that are cheaper due to subsidies from another country.
In other words, the competition for the buyer will be between companies operating under the same industry rules.
On the other hand, Kasyanova notes, Russian producers are not able to meet 50% of the domestic needs of compatriots in all items.
And in this situation, retailers will have to "pull" the share of Russian goods to half of the range.
This has led to fears that substandard products will be sold.
It is possible that foreign products with broken labels will be supplied under the guise of Russian products", the expert adds.
The negative impact of the introduction of quotas will be felt by the major trading networks, especially those that are more profitable to cooperate with importers.
It is only logical that foreign suppliers would suffer as well, since demand for their products would decline.
Litvinenko does not rule out that the law on quotas for domestic goods may also affect consumers.
The fact is that some Russian products may be inferior in quality to imported counterparts, while stores will be able to raise prices for the latter as a scarce commodity.
The idea of import substitution, which was forgotten in the early 2000s, was revived in February this year by economists due to the relentless devaluation of the ruble.
Now, with the difficult relationship with the West, the question of abandoning imported products is becoming even more urgent.
The law is designed to oblige retailers to take into account domestic manufacturers when forming orders to suppliers.
Then we will go much faster and more confidently on the way of import substitution, and the system of planning production for the necessary types of products will be created in a shorter time", says Oleg Nilov, a deputy.
The quota mechanism will be particularly effective for those agricultural sectors where the potential is particularly high, for example in the dairy sector, where imports accounted for 25%.
Our farmers are really capable of completely covering the shelves of Russian stores.
Meat production could also be a major driver.
As you know, the largest share of imports is kept by beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out that 65-70% of the production is still Russian", - says Kasyanova.
Experts believe that the introduction of quotas on domestic products will promote import substitution and can accelerate this process.
However, this initiative alone will not lead to import substitution, as a set of measures is needed, Litvinenko is sure.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be imported from abroad, which means that full import substitution will not occur, but significant steps will be taken in this direction.
In addition, it is not enough to set quotas, we still need to establish domestic production in the country to meet these quotas.
These quotas are just such guarantees", the expert says.
Premature diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more
Angelina Jolie and her brother James released a video in memory of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women who work in rural Australia face a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than those who live in cities.
Researchers analyzed the medical records of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, and found that only 35 percent survived five years after the diagnosis.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Institute for Medical Research reported that those living in rural and remote areas of the state were 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those living in urban areas.
FURTHER RESEARCH: New drugs may slow lung and ovarian cancer
Researchers tracked the women's medical history over seven years.
Dr. Jordan said that a woman's age at diagnosis, type of ovarian cancer, current disease status, and socioeconomic status also affected her survival.
Older women and those with cancer in the later stages at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
Those who lived in rural or remote areas of the state were 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those who lived in urban areas.
Although the study was not designed to determine why women living outside cities are more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that premature diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible factors.
"The disease is best treated by gynecologic surgeons, who are mainly in the big cities", she said.
While improving telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that increasing the number of out-of-home services that would allow professionals to treat women closer to home and support programs for people receiving treatment far from home could help.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographic location, the study found that longevity among women with ovarian cancer was rare, highlighting the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The research, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young mother from the Gold Coast, Elisha Nieve, was told she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
