Homeowners are down in the garden centers
This drop, driven by the exceptional decline in homeownership under 35, could see gardening centres losing tens of millions of pounds a year as today's young consumers reach "basic gardening age", according to a HTA study reported by the Financial Times.
According to the report, renters spend an average of 55 percent of what homeowners spend on gardening.
It cites the increasing number of people living in highly urbanized areas without gardens, the popularity of paving out front yards for parking and the reduction in garden size as other factors threatening the industry, which has an estimated annual sales of £5 billion.
Greater London, where homeownership fell from 61 percent to 43 percent in six years, has the lowest expenditure rate in the UK for household gardeners.
The HTA and the Royal Horticultural Society reported that renting a home and not having space for a garden does not mean that people cannot grow plants.
Guy Barter, chief gardening adviser at the RHS, said: "Growing plants in containers, for example, is particularly popular with tenants who can carry plants with them when they move".
The HTA report defined the period between 1997 and 2005 as the "golden age" of retail gardening goods as a result of the increase in homeownership and economic prosperity from the late 1980s to the mid-1990s.
It also predicts that the market will improve this year due to better weather after unfavorable conditions in March and April last year.
