The biggest Chinese companies are united against Alibaba
Chinese companies, including China's largest commercial real estate developer Dalian Wanda Group and internet giants Tencent Holdings (social networks, messenger, etc.) and Baidu (China's largest search engine), are creating a company that will compete in the online trading market with Alibaba.
But catching up with the Chinese Internet miracle, which has overtaken even its American rivals eBay and Amazon.com, will be a challenge.
The Union of Large
The companies plan to invest 5 billion yuan ($814 million) in the joint venture, 70% of which will be owned by Wanda and 15% each by the internet companies, according to a report by Wanda Group.
The company is planning to register in Hong Kong.
The joint venture will combine Baidu's search services with the popular social platform WeChat (the largest social network in China, with about 438 million users), Tencent and Wanda's infrastructure.
In addition to its chain of 40 high-end hotels, Wanda Group operates at least 49 commercial real estate properties across China and 40 shopping centers.
Last year , the company invested 50 billion yuan (more than $ 8 billion) in building a movie studio and theme park in Qingdao (a city in eastern China on the Yellow Sea).
The project is expected to attract more than 1 million visitors annually and generate $960 million in revenue.
In addition, Wanda owns the American cinema chain AMC Entertainment Holdings, making the company the largest cinema operator in the world.
By 2015, Wanda plans to equip all of its shopping malls, hotels and entertainment venues with e-commerce services, which will be developed by its rival Alibaba.
According to Dong Tse, who will lead the new company, the merger will allow Wanda to increase the number of users of its e-commerce services from 40 million to 100 million by next year.
The new platform is set to become the world's largest online-to-offline platform, said Dong Tse.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract buyers online so that they come to regular offline stores or buy other traditional services.
A classic example of O2O is coupon services like Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
"O2O is the biggest pie in online commerce", said Wanda CEO Wang Jianlin (quoted by Bloomberg).
"There is no real O2O platform in China right now, and in this situation, everyone has a roughly equal chance", he said.
China's e-commerce market is the largest in the world, and McKinsey & Co. estimates that it will more than triple by 2015 from 2011 to $395 billion.
The number of Chinese internet users has grown to 632 million, according to official statistics from Bloomberg: that's more than the population of any country in the world, except India.
And by 2015, that number is projected to grow to 850 million.
The Union of the Richest
Tencent CEO Ma Huaten was until recently China's richest man, but according to Bloomberg's billionaires index, Alibaba founder Jack Ma has already surpassed him by $5.5 billion.
Jack Ma's fortune is estimated at $21.8 billion, of which $11 billion is his stake in Alibaba.
Baidu CEO Robin Lee is now ranked third among China's richest people, while Wanda's Wang Jianlin is fourth.
"It's a very interesting battle to watch: the three richest people are joining forces to challenge the richest", said Cao Lei, director of the China e-commerce research center in Hangzhou, Bloomberg reported.
But he believes the new company is unlikely to be able to compete seriously with Alibaba immediately after its creation: "Rome can't be built in a day".
Alibaba's recent quarterly financial performance report shows that it is not easy to compete with not only new companies but also the established leaders of global e-commerce.
Alibaba is often described as something in between eBay and Amazon.com, but from April to June the Chinese company earned more than both of its American competitors combined.
Alibaba's net profit for the period is almost twice as high as the similar sum of its competitors - it has almost tripled year-on-year to $1.99 billion.
"Alibaba still has huge money-generating potential, thanks in large part to its mobile apps", commented an analyst from Hong Kong's Arete Research Service on Bloomberg's report.
According to an updated prospectus of Alibaba on the website of the US Securities and Exchange Commission, the number of active mobile users of the company's services in July was 188 million, which is significantly higher than the March figure (163 million people).
While 32.8% of all Alibaba transactions in the last quarter were on mobile devices.
Alibaba is going to announce the price of its shares before the IPO.
According to an average of 11 analysts polled by Bloomberg, the company could be valued at $187 billion after the sale of shares.
According to Bloomberg, Alibaba's debut on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) is likely to take place on September 16.
The company's road show preceding this event will kick off on September 3rd.
Alibaba's IPO is expected to be a record in NYSE history and raise about $20 billion.
The previous record for the largest amount of funds raised on U.S. exchanges was held by Visa, which made a $17.9 billion initial public offering in 2008.
