Construction facility estimates in Russia to be calculated in a new way
The Federal Antimonopoly Service is taking special control of pricing, regulating the construction industry, and connecting to the grid.
The FAS has established an expert council for the development of competition in the construction sector.
At its meeting, the head of the Housing, Communities and Construction and Natural Resources Control Department of the Federal Housing Administration Vadim Solovyov stated that "today's estimate of the construction facilities is absolutely incomprehensible".
The regulatory framework makes pricing opaque and can lead to unreasonable construction costs, the FAS believes.
And they propose that the cost of construction of state-owned facilities at the design stage be determined on the basis of market prices of constructive solutions instead of the current estimated norms and unit prices for technological operations.
These proposals are included in the roadmap and are now under consideration by the Ministry of Construction.
"The replacement of traditional construction estimates with calculations of structural elements should lead to less corruption in the industry", explained Vadim Solovyov.
Because the estimate now includes every bolt and nut, and it is not always possible to check everything, sometimes unscrupulous construction companies can bury "whole tractors" in the documentation.
The Ministry and the FAS agree.
"The first developments on the transition to calculating the cost of the construction elements are already there: methods have been developed for calculating the prices of the construction solutions, drawing up estimates on these indicators, - said "RGB" the head of the Department of urban planning and architecture of the Ministry of construction Elena Zhukova.
The road construction sector has been selected as a pilot project.
However, experts believe that the problem is much more serious.
As the head of the construction company "Profi-invest" Anatoly Demyanko told RGB, the estimate standards are long outdated, but no other mechanism has yet been proposed to the business.
"As for the proposed calculations for the structural elements, in practice this is difficult to implement, since buildings are often built using completely different technologies", he says.
It's no secret that the construction industry is largely a government enterprise.
According to the chairman of the board of the National Enterprise "Expert Community of State Procurement Professionals" Ekaterina Lezina, today the state is the most payment-able customer.
Vladimir Malakhov, deputy director of engineering at Rosatom's Industrial Capital Construction Center, noted that the market is conditionally divided into companies that have access to a portfolio of contracts and companies that have monopoly competencies and do not allow competitors to enter the market.
He believes that a transparent market can only be created if access to contracts is as secure as possible from anyone's controlling influence.
The expert council proposed to form a system of state contracts in such a way that the same contractor does not have the right to receive more than one contract for a sum of more than 1 billion rubles or several contracts for a sum of more than 1 billion rubles.
The Ministry of Construction believes that this approach should be evaluated in terms of the impact on business as well as the efficiency of construction management.
As Elena Zhukova explained, in this case it will be necessary to give the customer the functions of a general contractor, which will lead to an increase in the number of employees and budgetary costs for its maintenance.
The contracting authorities are required to provide the necessary information to the contractor to assess the quality of the work and its safety.
Often, such a breakdown will require determining who will be responsible for the security of the facility as a whole.
In addition, this approach may lead to the outflow of highly qualified public procurement participants due to the lack of interest in obtaining a public contract for an incomplete work volume and a small contract amount.
Alexander Yevstachenkov, deputy head of the expert-consultation center of the Institute of Purchases, believes that now the procedure of the state order has turned into a business game for the attention of the contractor.
And he gave an example: "A participant must indicate "specific indicators" when filling out an application without indicating the words: "or equivalent", "must be", "from", "more", "less", "analog", "or", "type", "analogous type", "not lower", "lower", "higher", "may", "may have", "may be", "before", "not earlier", "not higher", "is not allowed" and so on.
Thus, customers often abuse their right to impose requirements on the content of the application submitted by the contractors.
Another problem of the 44-FZ, according to Yevstachenkov, was the need to assess the quality of the work through the "paper" proposal of the participant at the stage of submitting the application.
The expert believes that when considering the application of a participant, only the qualification of the contractor can be evaluated, but not the quality of the work, which has not yet been started.
The quality of the work can only be assessed by accepting it.
The expert council also proposed moving marginal revenue from the top to the bottom echelon to eliminate intermediate contractors.
The chairman of the expert council, the state secretary, the deputy head of the FAS, Andrei Tsarikovsky, believes that this should not be done, because the general contractor should be responsible for the order.
Or else it will be like Arkady Raikin's famous "Atelier" reprise: "Do you have a complaint about buttons?"
Israeli children return to school after Gaza war
Thousands of Israeli children in areas near the Gaza Strip went back to school on Monday after spending the summer in bomb shelters as rockets and mines rained down on their settlements during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in Gaza remained closed as the territory rebuilt from the fighting.
The start of school brought a sense of joy and excitement to the rocket-affected settlements of southern Israel, but the traces of the fighting remained fresh.
In the southern city of Ashdod, the Pashosh kindergarten, which was hit by a missile, was cleaning up the debris from the walls and the children's sheds before the children arrived.
"We are a little scared, but we are looking forward to the future", said Ronit Bart, a resident of Kibbutz Saad and an English teacher at his school.
Many of the kids in our neighborhood really need to get back to a life of moderation.
Her 11-year-old daughter, Shani Bart, said that going back to school was "a little weird".
"It was a difficult time, and we never left our homes", she said.
President Reuven Rivlin visited a kibbutz near the Gaza border to express his support.
Before a ceasefire agreement ended the war last week, thousands of residents of border settlements like Saad stayed indoors or fled their homes to safer areas farther from the Gaza Strip to escape rocket and mortar fire.
Many residents of Nahal Oz, a settlement near the Gaza border where a 4-year-old Palestinian boy was killed by a shrapnel from a landmine, are unsure whether they should return.
The Ministry of Education said that about a dozen families still haven't returned.
Their children were sent to other schools at that time.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a town on the Gaza border that has been hit hard by Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to study hard and said: "We will do everything we can to educate you and keep you safe".
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite truce last Tuesday.
The ceasefire agreement immediately ended the fighting, but key issues remained unresolved, such as Hamas's demand to lift the Egyptian-Israeli blockade of Gaza and to open airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its arms and return the bodies of two Israeli soldiers killed in the war.
A new round of indirect talks is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
The war killed more than 2,100 Palestinians, three-quarters of them civilians, and at least 494 children, according to estimates by the Palestinian side and the UN.
Israel disputes these figures and claims that at least half of those killed were militants; despite this, it has not provided substantial evidence to support this claim.
On the Israeli side, 66 soldiers and six civilians were killed, including one Thai worker.
During the fighting, Hamas and other Gaza militants fired 4,591 rockets and mines into Israeli cities, mostly in the south.
The Israeli army, meanwhile, has carried out more than 5,000 airstrikes and other attacks.
As a result of Israeli attacks, thousands of homes in Gaza have been damaged and destroyed, and an estimated 250,000 people have taken refuge in more than 100 schools that have been converted into shelters.
With tens of thousands of people still in shelters and fighting continuing, education officials postponed the start of the school year last week.
"I hope that the school will open soon so that we can complete our education like children from all over the world and Jewish children", said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in a Gaza school.
According to a popular benchmark, real estate prices have shown the biggest winter increase in seven years.
The RP Data CoreLogic Hedonic home price index for housing prices in the Australian capital rose 1.1 percent in August, RP data reported on Monday.
