How people live in the oldest house in Ufa
In the former house of goldsmiths and mining workers Yevdokim and his son Ivan Demidov on October Revolution Street 57/1 (formerly Big Kazan) 18 apartments.
The 18th-century house has remained virtually unchanged since its construction, except for its old age.
Strangers come here as if on a field trip, and the residents suffer more than they rejoice from their privilege - the right to live in the oldest Ufa house, the walls of which commemorate the memory of the commander Alexander Suvorov.
The date of construction is not known, but historians point to two dates - 1730 and 1737.
But either way, it turns out the building is at least 300 years old.
The old yard, the door always open, the squeaky stairs.
The doors are close together, the walls are cracked, and the street is visible in the light from the stucco.
It seems like everything is on the up and up.
The locals say, "You don't think it is".
It is very difficult to live in a 18th-century wooden house, says Tatyana Lukyanova, a resident of apartment No. 3.
The site is in state care, but no money has been allocated for its maintenance for decades, and we feel like museum exhibits that the authorities have simply forgotten.
It was last renovated 40 years ago.
The walls are still a little rough, but the foundation is all rotted.
Many residents still use the toilet outside, but bathe once a week in a public bath.
How can you be content in such conditions?!
The road goes right under the windows, there's not even a pedestrian zone.
Tatiana pulls the curtain back.
Now you can see what you've only heard before: a stream of cars under the windows.
You see, the windows are always crumbling, we can't open the windows, and we're used to the noise.
Man gets used to everything, good and bad.
Our apartment is still in good shape, thanks to my husband, his hands are golden.
Besides, we have two rooms, three of us and our son.
Other families have much worse conditions, with ceilings on the second floor only a little over a meter and a half high.
To contrast, Tatyana offers to visit her neighbor from apartment No. 6 Ludmila Staroština.
A nice, hospitable woman on the doorstep offers a cup of coffee and says with a sad smile:
We have a one-room apartment, 14 square feet for four people, and we live there with my husband, my daughter, and my granddaughter.
I've been here since I was born, there's never been another living space, - Lyudmila looks around the room: antresols, two sofas with a "g"; one of them has a granddaughter with a laptop.
It's very small and not much different from the usual domestic interior: only the ceilings are beautiful, "historic".
But the ceiling is leaking regularly. The plumbing system is no good.
Lyudmila speaks of her apartment in a casual and surprising way, like an Italian whose house is on Roman ruins.
So it's a combination of the very old and the very recent, the everyday and the legendary:
The water main was cut about 40 years ago during the last renovation.
Then they made us a small kitchen in the corner and a toilet out of the old closet.
We live in the same apartment where Demidov and his family lived, the servants lived on the second floor.
Our apartment isn't privatized, so why?
The Ufa Real Estate Center says privatization is irrelevant.
We'll only get one room anyway, we can't ask for more.
Four months ago, they promised to move us, but they never did.
I'm not used to complaining, and I won't.
This apartment was the home of a dynasty: my grandparents, my mother and father, my husband and I, and my daughter and granddaughter.
Everything happened in that time.
For example, large rats were running around the kitchen.
Look at the walls of the wing, they're a meter thick!
They say the solution was mixed in the eggs, that's why it lasts so long.
The house is well built, thanks to Demidov!
Probably why no one's been killed by a collapsed ceiling or a pile of debris.
But the building is still dying slowly before our eyes: the boards and logs of the house are rotting, the floors have fallen down repeatedly, we poured cement, but it's all useless - the solution goes into the ground like a well.
They say there is a secret passageway under our room to the White River that was built by the Old Believers to protect us from danger.
They were being chased.
Lyudmila Starostina tells how some historian came to them, begging to let him start excavating in the apartment.
And then he convinced them to give him a place to live in exchange for his one-room apartment on October Avenue.
Lyudmila refused the historian:
Where are the four of us going alone?
There's a small chance they'll make it bigger.
If we agreed to the exchange, we wouldn't have won anything.
The Old Ones, however, won nothing.
Ludmila's biggest dream is to have them moved in and her daughter and 16-year-old granddaughter have their own room.
So two families were given a two-bedroom apartment instead of the not-so-magnificent ruins that two generations now live in.
A cute, miniature girl Olesya Karsakova from apartments 11 and 12 shows the second floor of the house.
There, her large family lives in two small rooms, called apartments, with a total area of 23 square meters.
There are seven of us, two children.
You can see the conditions.
The plaster falls off in pieces, as do the window frames, the walls in the kitchen and the rooms with the through holes.
The tap water is only cold all year round.
Walking through the apartments of the oldest house in Ufa, you can see that the most fortunate of all were the couple Lavrentyev from apartment No. 4.
They're in the most spacious rooms on the first floor.
You're right, there's plenty of room!
It's a 75-square-foot facility, three people.
We live in the rooms where Suvorov stayed during his stay in Ufa, according to legend, - says family head Alexander Dmitrievich Lavrentiev.
The ceilings are high, spacious.
The bad news is, everything around you is cracking, falling apart, falling apart.
The neighbors must have told you already!
The most painful part was the floors: the wooden planks were rotting, the ground was literally moving from under our feet.
I've put up the props, the wedges, there's nothing in the room, and in the other room we're walking, swinging, everything's so shaky.
Alexander Dmitrievich can tell you more about the house of the merchant Yevdokim Demidov than any tour guide.
He treats the goldsmith like one of his own, speaks of him with admiration.
Indeed, the personality was extraordinary: the owner of the Kagi and Uzyan plants built houses, cast cannons and bells, held the Ural mines.
The heirs of the merchant estate are proud of their ancestors, but they no longer want to live under the same roof with history.
I settled here as a child in the 1940s, says Alexander Dmitrievich.
The wooden carriage houses, stables, and guard booths were later demolished.
In 1968, they tried to clean up our house, but something stopped them.
The story repeated in 2014: they were again given new housing.
We were working as a team, getting all the paperwork together, going through the proper procedures, and suddenly we found out that the move to the apartments was postponed to 2015 or 2016.
We don't believe in all this anymore...
Two years ago, Lavrentiev went to the Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Bashkortostan to find out about the fate of the house.
The tenant was turned away.
They would send it from one table to another, and then, as a joke, hand out a paper without a signature or seal: "The Ministry of Culture has no objection to the resettlement of the residents".
I even feel like our house is long gone from the city map, because it was 57 first, then 57A, now 57/1.
It's like it was torn down in the '70s.
"Russian Planet" has appealed to the head of the information and analytical work sector of the Ufa land resources department Vladimir Barabash.
The house at 57/1 October Revolution Street is included in the program of old housing.
I can't be held responsible for the actions of the officials of the 1970s, but I do know that at that time there was a plan to demolish all the old houses, despite their historical significance.
Fortunately, this did not happen, and the decision of the modern authorities to restore all the old houses on the street of the October Revolution, which represent architectural value, is successfully being implemented.
The residents are to be moved to new apartments soon.
According to Barabash, the restoration of the Demidov House will be carried out by Italian specialists who participated in the restoration of buildings in Venice.
Now in Italy, the architectural biennial is taking place, and the project "Old Ufa" is presented there among others.
I hope that by 2016 the entire Old Kazan Street will be restored, - says the official.
The houses will look exactly as they did three centuries ago.
Demidov's house will probably be a museum open to all.
In addition, the government has decided to make the street pedestrian-only on weekends.
Unfortunately, we can't do it on weekdays, because the city's too busy.
Vladimir Barabash promises to move people from the future museum in 2015.
However, they are unlikely to be satisfied: Their new apartments will be the same size as their current ones.
Only from another era.
