4 tips for better underwater photography and video
If you want to take pictures or video underwater, you have a variety of equipment options.
The cheapest option is a waterproof soapbox, such as the Nikon Coolpix AW120, or an action camera, such as the GoPro Hero3+ Silver Edition, both of which sell for about $300.
I took these pictures at a family reunion using a couple of cameras, all for about $350.
No matter what equipment you use, there are a few rules to follow to get the best results.
Check your equipment.
Even if you have a waterproof camera, make sure the battery and other compartments are tightly sealed.
Also, set your camera to the type of photos or videos you're going to take.
Some cameras have shooting modes or object types that optimize exposure for darkened underwater conditions.
And before you jump in, figure out how deep your equipment can go.
Some of the chambers are only designed to be five feet long, others are 50 or 60 feet long.
Check out our buyer's guide and digital camera ratings for both conventional and waterproof models.
Take a few shots, because a lot of them won't work.
The washers are the LCDs that help you compose the images, whereas action cameras don't usually have them.
Even if you have a LCD, it's hard to see underwater, and the framing is a random process.
So, take a few shots.
Also, if your camera has a serial mode that shoots multiple frames with slightly different exposure settings, use it.
Stay on the surface.
The amount of light decreases significantly the deeper you dive.
If possible, stay near the surface when you shoot in a pool, river or ocean.
It also allows you to convey more color in photos; the deeper you go, the less color you see.
Swim closer to the target.
This is great advice for shooting on land, but it's even more important underwater because of the dim lighting conditions.
Especially important if you're shooting with an action camera: This equipment often comes with a fixed, wide-angle lens, which means you'll have to get close to the subjects if you want to fill the frame.
