It was mesothelioma, an incurable cancer that affects the pleura, or the lining of the lungs.
For most cancers, it's hard to pinpoint the exact cause.
Although some smokers get lung cancer, for example, not all lung cancer patients have smoked.
But it's different with mesothelioma.
In almost all cases, the cause is exposure to asbestos, a fibrous building material once called a "miracle" but now known to be deadly.
For most of us, mesothelioma is a disease that can be ignored.
Asbestos, after all, is a thing of the past.
The most dangerous type of asbestos has not been used in the UK since the 1960s, when a recommendation for an industrial ban came into force.
Even when it was in use, only people in specific industries worked closely with it: pipe insulators, builders, carpenters, and dock workers, for example.
An industrial toxin from another era, it hardly seems to be a cause for concern today.
But that kind of calm is wrong.
It turns out that the UK is at the peak of the mesothelioma epidemic today.
More people die from mesothelioma here than in any other country on the planet.
With an annual death rate of about 2,500, more than twice as many people die from this disease as from car accidents.
Annual deaths from mesothelioma since 1980 and projected future deaths in the UK
The reason we're feeling its deadly effects now is that while asbestos use has been illegal for many years (all types of asbestos were eventually outlawed in 1999), it usually takes decades for mesothelioma to develop.
And the onset of mesothelioma is not limited to veterans of the construction industry.
Asbestos was, and in many cases remains, a contaminant in the homes where we live, the offices where we work, the schools where we go to school, and the shops where we shop.
As a result, mesothelioma does not care about class, income, occupation or age.
The bastions of the elite, from London's trendy department stores to private schools, turned out not to be the answer.
The parliament building is asbestos-infested.
Even the hospitals that are designed to treat us have become reservoirs of this deadly carcinogen.
Andrew Lawson wasn't old.
He wasn't a pipe wrench.
