Few people really know much about asbestos.
Actually, asbestos is not a single substance but a group of six minerals.
They get their name from the word asbestos, which means a fibrous structure that gives them strength and flexibility.
Of these six, three were often used in construction.
Chrysotile, commonly known as white asbestos, is much more commonly found in buildings today.
It was used in roofing panels, floor tiles, thermal insulation of pipes, boiler seams, even in car brake pads.
It is less deadly than other forms of asbestos, but it is recognized by the European Union and the World Health Organization as a "serious health hazard" that can lead to death.
However, brown asbestos (amozite) and blue asbestos (crocidol) are more dangerous.
Britain was once the world's largest importer of brown asbestos, and experts suggest that "there is strong, albeit indirect, evidence to suggest that it is the main cause of the exceptionally high number of mesothelioma cases [in Britain]".
