Genetic disorders are often misdiagnosed
The Briton said she spent years thinking she was going to die after being misdiagnosed.
Caryn Rogers spent much of her teenage years thinking she had only a few years to live after being diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease, a group of inherited disorders that cause nerve damage outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK reports that misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT because so little is known about the condition.
Approximately 23,000 people in the UK are thought to have PTSD, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, unsteady gait and pinched toes.
Patients may experience numbness or pain, and the condition is not curable and progresses, meaning that symptoms worsen over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedrich ataxia (AF), a condition for which the prognosis was very poor.
Rogers thought she'd be wheelchair bound by the time she was 18 and dead before she was 30.
A mother of two, now 51, said: "As a child, I knew that I could not do what others could.
I fell every day, and it took me more time.
I could never skate or skate with other kids, and I was bullied a lot at school for my walking and running.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several operations to free her Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she looked at her medical records when her doctor came out of the room, and it said she had AF.
"I felt guilty because I had stuck my nose where it didn't belong, and so I didn't tell anyone, but I went home, found information about the condition in the library, and wrote to the AF Association", she said.
When I got the information back, I was shocked and experienced the most terrible panic that could be experienced.
I thought I'd be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I was 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in the meantime.
I went through this alone, and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she was 17, she realized that her walking ability had not deteriorated as much as she thought, and she asked her doctor about it.
He just stood up, hugged me, and said, "Honey, I don't think you have this disease because you'd be in a wheelchair by now".
I think you have something that's a lot less life-threatening.
After a few genetic tests, they found a C.M.T.
"When he explained what the SPC was, I thought I had a lucky ticket", she said.
The UK charity CKD has launched CKD awareness month to try to raise awareness of the disease.
The tax burden on Washington businessmen is rising as the economy recovers .
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales and new jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local tax bills for companies across the country have risen moderately in the past year as the economic recovery has accelerated, according to a new study released last week, and companies in the Washington area are no exception.
Companies in the District, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $27.6 billion to the state and local treasury in fiscal 2013, up 3.8 percent from the $26.6 billion collected in 2012.
The state and local business tax burden last year increased 4.3 percent to $671 billion, up from 3.9 percent a year earlier, and this was the third straight year of growth after back-to-back years of declining bills in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes rose faster, 4.3 percent, than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study that was conducted by the professional services firm Ernst & Young and the State Tax Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the county's tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from business taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland's tax revenue comes from corporations.
Virginia, at 28 percent, brings the lowest tax revenue, proportionally, from entrepreneurs.
The tax revenue growth is largely driven by companies returning to previous levels of property values, researchers say, which have raised property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three consecutive years of growth of less than 1 percent.
While a large share of these revenues are in large states like California, New York and Texas, the same seems to be happening in the Washington area.
Companies in the District, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012 - a 4.2 percent increase over the previous year.
However, the observed return on property value has no similar effect on the increase in tax revenue at the state and local level in Maryland, where property taxes barely exceed one-fifth of corporate tax bills.
Virginia and D.C. companies pay about half of their state and local tax bills in property taxes.
"What's happening in Maryland is that so much of their property, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, is owned by either the government or nonprofits that don't pay property taxes", said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the state's Tax Center.
So Maryland has to rely on much more, like income taxes to pay for the same services that other states have.
The recent increase in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be entirely explained by the recovery of the real estate market.
Entrepreneurs' incomes also seem to be improving, according to this data.
Companies in the region filed a $2.3 billion statewide corporate income tax return, up $2.1 billion from 2012.
Maryland collected $1 billion in corporate income tax revenue, the most in the region.
Although trends are in one direction, the tax burden on local entrepreneurs is not increasing at the same rate in all three locations.
The growth rate in the District of Columbia was at the same level as the national average of 4.3 percent, whereas growth in Maryland was much faster, at 4.9 percent.
Only Virginia saw a lower-than-average 4.1 percent increase in tax revenue.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of the three jurisdictions (each of which had the same corporate rate), at 6 percent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 percent, while in the District it is relatively high at 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that Virginia has lower taxes for entrepreneurs at the state and local levels and a generally more favorable climate for entrepreneurs when it comes to taxes than Maryland.
The county was not evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is under competitive pressure from its neighbor to the south.
North Carolina recently signed legislation lowering the corporate rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, just like Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to meet its tax revenue targets next year, this bill could bring the corporate income tax rate even higher to 3 percent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington area seem to be doing better and thus paying more in state and local taxes, according to a recent study.
The taxes for entrepreneurs paid as individual income taxes by small business owners -- the transitional structure that most small businesses are built on -- in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia rose 20 percent last year to $2.4 billion, much faster than the taxes for entrepreneurs overall.
Researchers say the trend and increase in business tax revenues across the country is likely to continue this year, with state and local sales tax revenues up 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington area may fall behind as federal spending cuts affect the region's labor market.
