All kings can
The debut album from Royal Blood is on sale, the new hope of British rock, bringing rock duos from clubs straight to the stadiums.
Royal Blood has been on stage for just over a year, but they've already earned a nomination for a BBC Music Award, a warm-up tour with Arctic Monkeys and a visit to the dressing room of a New York concert from Jimmy Page himself.
Their debut album of the same name received 100,000 pre-orders a few months before its release, and the contract to release it is in the portfolio of the major label Warner Music.
Given the current dismal state of the music industry, it's a strange situation, because this isn't the new Lana Del Rey or another sweet-talking representative of the new R'n'B, but a duo of British-looking bulls playing at the same level of volume and intensity that was last in fashion a couple of decades ago.
In general, the stakes on the first album were particularly high and justified.
The duo has a name that's been taken advantage of by a few desperate hairy metal fans, and the blood of kings they think runs through their veins is clear.
This is, of course, primarily about the heroes of the past level of Led Zeppelin: like the great quartet, Royal Blood set out to shake up the stagnant blood of British rock, taking it to new heights.
It's probably too early to predict the success of this venture, but there are some things we can say.
A dozen songs in thirty minutes or less is not so much a demonstration of phenomenal compositional talent as a confident and powerful declaration of intent.
Some of the virtues of the individual tracks, of course, cannot be denied: for example, the pilot single "Out Of The Black" is characterized by being remembered not for the melodic line, but for the drum part.
Musicians joke that this song is actually easier to tune than to sing.
Also worth noting is the powerful "Little Monster" and the closing track "Better Strangers" with a Shakespearean quote in the title.
But the truth is, each of these songs will sound great at a heavy rock party, but when played in a row, they all blend into a more or less homogeneous canvas.
And that's not necessarily a bad thing, quite the opposite.
Royal Blood's strength is that they don't claim the accolades of the new Lennon and McCartney (rather aiming for the successors to Motörhead), but have brought numerous rock duos out of the ghetto of indie clubs.
Their music, while varied, is designed for stadiums, a space designed for fewer than a couple thousand people, and it's obviously cramped.
The secret is partly in the clever use of the bass, which replaced the guitar in the usual format invented in the early days of The White Stripes.
However, it is not just the instruments that matter, but also the very approach to songwriting.
The retro rock heroes of the Zeroes had a hard time breaking out of the postmodern paradigm, and were reluctant to recognize themselves as independent creative entities rather than mere epigons.
Royal Blood already sounds so powerful and bold that this stress successfully drapes some of the secondary and hard-hitting nature of the music material.
After all, who says rock's got to be smart?
Amazon buys Twitch for $1.04 billion
AMAZON has just confirmed what Information reported on Friday morning: The online store - and video producer, and a hundred other things - is buying streaming video service Twitch for $1.04 billion ($970 million).
This news came as a surprise, not because no one expected Twitch to be sold, but because many expected YouTube to be the buyer.
Three months ago, the sale of Twitch to Google for a billion dollars seemed complete, and it seemed natural.
Twitch, founded just three years ago as Justin.tv, set out to be a general-purpose streaming service - a real-time version of YouTube.
Instead, it quickly evolved into a platform where gamers streamed their in-game moments; "YouTube for real-time gaming", according to Business Insider.
The Twitch interface.
And "let's play", a genre of videos in which know-it-alls give (mostly old) games a treatment, like in "Mystery Theater", is already popular on YouTube.
The thing is, YouTube is mentioned a lot when describing Twitch, so the news that YouTube is acquiring Twitch was met with little interest, a classic example of a well-established tech company buying a potential competitor.
It's a mystery why the YouTube deal failed, given that it was reportedly willing to pay as little as Amazon.
All we have right now is a statement from Twitch CEO Emmet Shear: "We chose Amazon because they believe in our community, they share our values and long-term goals, and they want to help us achieve them faster".
Another secret, frankly, is the incredible success of Twitch.
For snobs like me who say they'd rather play sports than watch them, it's hard to see the appeal of watching games instead of picking up a joystick.
It's one thing to watch a friend's shoulder at 3 a.m. as she crawls through Resident Evil, and quite another to watch some stranger get shot 20 times in a row in Call of Duty.
All the games you could be watching right now.
Another problem is that many of today's most popular games are for one person, so watching them without controlling the viewing angle can be a recipe for a headache worthy of Do It Right.
I'll admit, the speed runs in which the Roger Bannisters of our electronic age complete entire games in record time are entertaining.
But unless it's a game or a comedy genius, it's unlikely his Twitch channel will be interesting at all.
But what do skeptics like me know?
Twitch has 55 million unique visitors per month, and it's the fourth-largest peak Internet traffic source.
How exactly is Amazon going to make money off of this?
It's hard to imagine that Twitch would fold into Amazon Instant Video as elegantly as YouTube could just swallow Twitch.
But Twitch has something that any company would love to have: the crowd of young men that advertisers dream of.
As Twitch CEO Shear said, Amazon and Twitch "both believe in the future of gaming", and the channel shows no signs of fading, even as a - oh - spectacular sport.
