Deputies proposed to speed up the entry into force of the law on personal data
If the initiative succeeds, data of Russians will not be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015.
The draft law was introduced in the State Duma, which provides for the transfer of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is in the legislative activity database of the lower house.
Its authors were the deputies of the State Duma Vadym Denegin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Yevgeny Fedorov ("United Russia"), Vladimir Parahin ("Justice Russia") and Alexander Yushchenko (KPRF).
According to the authors of the initiative, this change will contribute to a more efficient and effective protection of the rights of Russian citizens to the protection of personal data and the secrecy of correspondence in information and telecommunications networks.
The law, which parliamentarians are rushing to enact, requires that personal data of Russians processed via the Internet be stored on the territory of the Russian Federation.
It also makes it mandatory to record, systematize, store, store, clarify and extract personal data of Russian citizens in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as to indicate information about the location of such databases.
In addition, the law grants Roskomnadzor the right to restrict access to information processed in violation of the Russian legislation in the field of personal data on the basis of a court decision.
The law also proposes the creation of so-called "black lists" of violating websites - an automated information system "Register of violators of personal data subjects".
This law was passed by the State Duma in the summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrey Lugovoy and Vadim Denkin from the LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from the KPRF.
Dengen and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current bill to postpone the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who don't have data centers in Russia will have to pay rent
Commenting on the bill introduced today in the State Duma, the first deputy head of the Duma Committee on Information Policy Leonid Levin said that he sees no problems in postponing the date of entry into force of the law on personal data protection.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own storage of personal data of Russians in the territory of the Russian Federation, will be able to rent them, for example, "from Rostelecom, which has repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers for rent and already provides their servers, from Mail Group, from Western companies, which today already provide their servers".
"In addition, there are several independent data centers willing to cooperate in this area", he added.
"If companies decide to comply with the law and continue to operate in the territory of the Russian Federation, I see no problems - they will get technological opportunities to be located", Levin summed up.
The controversial bill
Immediately after the bill was published, the Russian Electronic Communications Association expressed concern that if the bill is passed, Russians will no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
In particular, online booking of airline tickets and hotels is a concern.
According to the association, "the bill deprives subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation of the right to dispose of their own data, imperatively determining that their recording, systematization, etc. should be provided only in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation".
The statement of the RAEEC emphasizes that a more effective measure would be to create a mechanism to inform the user about where the recording is carried out, systematizing his personal data.
In this case, the child can choose where the activities will be carried out.
The adoption of similar laws on "localization" of personal data in other countries has led to the decline of global services and significant economic losses.
