How to Save on University Textbooks
With college textbooks costing more than $1,000 a year for many students, Matt Schroeder, who is about to enter his second year, has come up with a clever way to cut costs.
He devised a system of borrowing books from high school students, offering them nominal compensation to delay their sale.
"My math textbook, which normally costs $180, I got for a semester for $10 and a Chick-fil-A cookie", says Schroeder, 19, who attends Covenant College in Georgia.
The required literature for the last semester would cost $430, he says.
He spent $120.
According to the College Board, the average student spends more than $1,200 a year on textbooks and study materials, but students have a number of options for reducing those costs.
Students are increasingly choosing online stores and creative ideas like Schroeder's.
Book rental is becoming increasingly popular, allowing students to use a book during the semester, and often costing significantly less than buying one.
Nibo Incorporated, which owns more than 250 university bookstores, reports that book sales have doubled since 2011.
Industry research shows that about a quarter of the books in university bookstores were rented during the past spring semester, says Trevor Meyer, vice president of Nibo.
Less than half of all books are purchased in university bookstores, according to the National Association of University Stores.
Here's an introductory course on the best ways to make a good deal.
Shopping online
Sometimes, if you go online, the price of a new book can be one-third of what you'd see in a university bookstore.
The ninth edition of "Mathematical Analysis" by Ron Larson, Bruce Edwards and Robert Hostetler costs about $290 per price tag, but a new copy can be purchased for $239.99 at Chegg.com, which specializes in textbook sales.
Buying used
If you don't mind any scratches or damage, used textbooks are a good option.
"Analytic" is for sale for $93.49 in second hand on Chegg.com.
Matt Cassaday, 25, a fourth-year student at Brigham Young University, says he paid 42 cents on Amazon.com for a second-hand copy of the textbook "Media Strategic Solutions: Understanding the Business Side of the Advertising Business".
The book sold for $48 a new one.
Teachers, such as Ingrid Bracey, director of College Without Walls at the University of Massachusetts, Amherst, urge students to ask their professors if they can use previous editions.
Sometimes updates are not essential to the class.
In such cases, old editions can often be found for a very small fraction of the cost of the latest edition.
In addition to Chegg and Amazon, Half.com, owned by eBay Inc., is a popular alternative for buying used books.
Rented
You should consider renting textbooks if you are good enough to handle them, remember to return them and not want to keep them after the course.
You can save over 80% on the cost of a new book.
For example, one student was able to rent "Analysis of Mathematics" for a semester for about $20.
Find out the rules of the bookstore where you pick up the books, including any fines you may be subjected to for marks, underlining, and damage.
If you rent a book, remember that if you do not return the book, the fine may even exceed the cost of the new copy.
E-books
E-books instead of traditional textbooks are another option.
Sometimes such books are actually rented by purchasing an electronic license for a certain period from distributors, such as Amazon.com, Chegg and Barnes & Noble Inc.
Renting "Analytic Math" on Chegg.com for six months is going to cost about $61.
Bracey says that students studying literature can often find the best prices, since many classics are now available for free download, whereas literature in the natural sciences and engineering can be quite expensive.
Look around, no matter what.
Joe Galt, 29, who is about to start law school at Pepperdine, recommends using the ISBN number to find out the price of a book, as this ensures that you are looking for exactly the text you need.
Before ordering online, Galt says, make sure the book is in stock.
He learned that lesson the hard way.
The book he bought was delayed for four weeks, and he eventually paid full price at the university bookstore.
