"Euro-protocol" instead of the DHS reference
Payments by casco will be possible without a GIBDD certificate - so the Central Bank intends to stimulate the introduction of the "Euro-protocol" in Russia.
The Bank of Russia has developed a draft guideline according to which from September 1 this year, the insured motorist will be able to do without a GIBD certificate to receive payments for the helmet.
It is true that we are only talking about cases where the accident was registered under the "European protocol" without the participation of the traffic police.
So if there were only two cars involved in the accident, no one was physically injured, the damage was within the designated limit, and both drivers agreed on who was to blame for the accident.
From August 2, the limit of payments under the "Euro-protocol" is 50 thousand rubles, and from October 1 in Moscow, St. Petersburg, as well as in Moscow and Leningrad regions it will be increased to 400 thousand rubles.
The point is that even in the case of minor injuries, in situations where the accident can be registered under the "European protocol", the drivers involved in the accident often call the traffic police.
Because if you had a helmet policy, you couldn't get reimbursement without a DHS certificate.
The parameters prescribed in the draft directive are designed to eliminate this obstacle in the way of introducing the "Euro-protocol" in Russia.
According to them, the maximum payment for a crash without the help of the DHS should not be lower than the limit of the "European Protocol".
However, it cannot be higher than the limit set in the helmet insurance contract.
The idea is certainly useful and theoretically can relieve both traffic and roadwork.
But it's not likely to please drivers or insurance companies.
The latter are already talking about the serious threat of increased fraud, which may be caused by the introduction of new rules for cash payments.
As for drivers, it is hard to imagine what work will have to be done to overcome the original Russian conservatism.
The driver will often wait hours for the inspector to report a minor accident because it is more reliable.
