The savings certificate will be made anonymous and irrevocable
The Treasury wants to ban deposit-only certificates, but it's going to allow banks to make them look like a permanent deposit.
The Treasury is drafting a bill that would ban the issuance of savings certificates.
The latter has been gaining popularity as the rates are higher than for bank deposits.
The fact is that the deposit insurance system does not cover the depositors' savings certificates, and they are cheaper for the bank because you do not have to make a deposit into the Deposit Insurance Agency (DIA).
The piquant thing is that this step is planned to be taken because of small and medium-sized banks that distribute such certificates, and Sberbank and Bank of Moscow will suffer from it, which, according to the ASV, control 98% of the profile market.
The Bank of Moscow's share, according to the agency, is about 3.5%.
The problem, the bank explains, is that customers of a small bank that has bought a certificate like this try to get money from the bank if the bank revokes its license.
Some depositors, who are not financially literate enough to buy a savings certificate on the holder's behalf, may assume that their investment is insured.
The lack of insurance payments for these certificates in case of revocation of the license from the bank can lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In the agency's practice, there have been cases where holders of pre-presentation certificates have tried to collect insurance compensation through the court", the agency said.
The problem, of course, is made up.
Because no one will pay the buyers of the certificates anyway, because they are not legally entitled to reimbursement from the state.
If the instrument were not insured in the ASV, the ban would also apply to metal accounts where citizens' funds are recorded in grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
These accounts don't get into the deposit insurance system either, but they're not being investigated.
The fact is, most likely, that the certificate of title is a very convenient security that can actually act as a quasi-currency.
At the same time, their movement is practically uncontrollable: any bank customer can buy a certificate, transfer it to any citizen, and before cashing out, such a certificate can change many owners.
It's no coincidence that the bill says that a savings certificate must be a registered security that must be kept in a depository.
And to sweeten the pot for the banks, they're allowed to issue certificates without the right to early redemption.
So, the kind of no-deposit deposit that bankers have been dreaming about for a long time.
