Senior analyst at the Belarusian Institute of Strategic Studies Denis Melyantsov is confident that Brussels will no longer be able to talk to Minsk in the same tone as before.
"The fact that Catherine Ashton met face-to-face with Lukashenko gives reason to believe that relations with the EU will continue to thaw", he told "Ogyna".
This iceberg has a hidden part: the Belarusian authorities began preparing for the breakthrough long before the November Maidan in Kiev - in the summer of 2013.
"Results have been achieved with the EU - successful negotiations on visa simplification and readmission, dialogues on modernization", the source of the report said.
The states even lifted some of the sanctions.
As for the Ukrainian events, they themselves and the reaction of the Belarusian leadership to them only fueled this process.
Minsk, on the one hand, managed to keep relations with Ukraine warm enough not to lose much in mutual trade, and President Poroshenko could come to Belarus for talks.
On the other hand, the Belarusian leader, who de jure did not recognize the annexation of Crimea to Russia and called for punishing pro-Russian militiamen in Donbas with all severity, did not quarrel with Moscow.
Minsk has not left the Customs Union, nor the CSTO, and in Baranovich is a Russian airbase.
Brussels and Washington have noticed the balanced position of Minsk on the Ukrainian issue - and have assessed it, Belarusian experts are confident.
How successful Lukashenko's move towards political diversification will be will be seen by how often Minsk will host EU+TC meetings in the near future.
The press service of EU High Representative for Foreign Affairs and Diplomacy Catherine Ashton was unable to promptly answer questions about what Brussels expects from the new format of relations.
