Boredom is sinful.
Frank Miller and Robert Rodriguez's Sin City 2: The Woman to Kill For did not revolutionize the world as you might expect.
The first Sin City (2005), filmed with minimal but symbolic participation by Quentin Tarantino, revolutionized the relationship between cinema, comics and literary noir.
The sequel is also revolutionary in its own way: in the sense that it breaks the fundamental chain of thesis-antithesis-synthesis for modern thinking (if we understand thesis as the noir universe, and antithesis as the comic book cosmos).
From now on, it should read: "thesis - antithesis - chaos".
Sin City 2 is chaotic on both the dramatic and the philosophical levels: both times it's chaotic in the bad sense of the word.
Yes, some of the characters are familiar from the first "City", although, here, the bully Marv (Micky Rourke), remembers, died in the electric chair, and here, nothing, only manages to grab - as a folk soldier - from the air knives and other axes with strangulation.
But the old people are literally being elbowed by the newcomers, like they're breaking into town from some other movie, whose meaning and plot the audience is told not to worry about.
So, his story, shamelessly told by the authors in the most interesting place, the super-lucky player Johnny (Joseph Gordon-Levitt).
His is with the lustful, frigid Eve Lord (Eva Green) and her vengeful Dwight (Josh Brolin).
But this confusion, in which Dwight's face is, say, indistinguishable from Johnny's - especially since faces, like other body parts, are removed from characters with inexorable regularity - is not a problem, and not even a half-problem.
These aren't people, we realize they're archetypes of the noir: the fatal bitch, the overconfident gambler, the honey trap sex detective, the corrupt, stubborn senator.
Well, when an archetype waltzes with an archetype and the archetype chases after it, it's not a movie anymore, it's abstract painting.
And to ask abstract painting questions about the logic of the plot is just ridiculous.
Besides, even in this chaotic world, there is something permanent.
The war whores of the first City still hold a circular defense against the forces of darkness besieging their hometown.
And Detective Hartigan's ghost is not a ghost, and he'll come to the lighthouse, and Bruce Willis is always a sight to behold.
The main problem with Sin City 2 is something else.
Frank Miller was good at combining comics and noir as a painter, and as a director, he was good at reversing the notion of how to bring comics to the screen.
Comics and noir are two aggressively opposed "realities".
The modern comic book phenomenon began in the late 1920s, when Dashiell Hammett's novels "Bloody Harvest" (1929), "The Maltese Falcon" (1930) and "The Glass Key" (1931) created the canon of the noir, then called the hard-boiled school.
Or pulp fiction.
Comics have given Hollywood dozens of heroes, from the spinach-eating sailor Popeye to Superman, Batman and detective Dick Tracy to Hulk, Thor, Spider-Man and other "avengers".
But there was something wrong with any comic book-based movie: The characters were so determined not to grow flesh on screen that they were left to pretend to be in the "real" world around them.
In a nutshell, they were completely deprived of "existence".
Noir, on the other hand, is the most existential genre in world literature.
After the world wars, the traditional novel - with its experiences, characters, family scandals, and historical background - lost all credibility.
What Forsyth, what Tibo and Rugon-Makka, what even Bolkonsky and Rostov are even conceivable after Verdun, Auschwitz and Hiroshima?
This novel quietly mutated into a soap opera, and the crime novel - that is, by definition, the marginal novel - rose to the level of philosophical prose.
Hammett learned firsthand what it was like to be a paramedic at the front.
He was a communist.
As, by the way, there were at least close to the Communist Party and such pillars of the genre as writers Horace McCoy and Jim Thompson, directors Jules Dassin, Joseph Loisy, Edward Dmytryk.
So the noir archetype they've set is, first, rude and cynical, and second, purely social.
