Anger is the most universal and functional emotion in the human being.
Angry facial expressions are biologically universal to humankind, and each organ and muscle group involved in making them is not random, but an additional means of expressing power and threat, researchers in Australia and the United States have found.
They reported their findings in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and a brief summary of the findings can be found in a press release from the University of California, Santa Barbara.
Angry facial expressions - raised and lowered eyebrows, slanted lips, puffy nostrils - are the same across cultures, even among children who have never seen a face that was born blind, says Aaron Sell, the study's lead author.
In a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists found that anger is a key emotion for effective conflict resolution.
The more physical damage one person can do to another, the more he has the ability to dictate his terms, which he communicates to the other person through anger.
The researchers found support for another hypothesis: Physically strong people are more likely to be angry and abusive, to feel entitled to impose unfavorable conditions on others, and to prefer violent methods to peaceful conflict resolution.
Based on the fact that anger is primarily a "commodity emotion", the researchers decided that the movements of each of the seven groups of muscles that produce an angry facial expression should make the angry individual appear more powerful and dangerous to the interlocutor - and thus force them to agree to his terms as soon as possible to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers modeled a computer face with each of the seven elements of an angry face, and showed them to informants.
Although lowered eyebrows or a raised chin alone did not make a face look angry, the subjects in the study were unanimous in their opinion that a person with these features was physically stronger.
Man's anger, like that of animals, is a threat: an exaggerated display of his own power, forcing him to yield and submit.
Man puffs his nostrils and presses his lips together for the same purpose as a frog that puffs itself up or a baboon that shows its fangs.
"Anger is triggered by the refusal of the other person to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes a form that most effectively demonstrates to the opposite side the consequences of that refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of an angry face are arbitrary, they all express the same thing", noted anthropologist John Tobey.
